{"id":"1110.0868","submitter":"Max Glick","authors":"Max Glick","title":"On singularity confinement for the pentagram map","comments":"37 pages, 25 figures. Various changes, mostly to section 8","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The pentagram map, introduced by R. Schwartz, is a birational map on the\nconfiguration space of polygons in the projective plane.\n  We study the singularities of the iterates of the pentagram map. We show that\na \"typical\" singularity disappears after a finite number of iterations, a\nconfinement phenomenon first discovered by Schwartz. We provide a method to\nbypass such a singular patch by directly constructing the first subsequent\niterate that is well-defined on the singular locus under consideration. The key\ningredient of this construction is the notion of a decorated (twisted) polygon,\nand the extension of the pentagram map to the corresponding decorated\nconfiguration space.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 4 Oct 2011 23:28:34 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 4 Mar 2012 23:27:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-03-06"}
{"id":"1110.0869","submitter":"Fred Jegerlehner","authors":"Fred Jegerlehner","title":"Comment on H --> gamma gamma and the role of the decoupling theorem and\n  the equivalence theorem","comments":"15 pages, 5 figures; including addendum and update concerning Ref.\n  [37] (Christova, Todorov), references added","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  I am commenting on the paper Gastmans, Wu and Wu, which recently obtained new\nsupport by a paper by Christova and Todorov, about a new calculation of the H\n--> gamma gamma rate mediated by the W boson loop, and the lack of decoupling\nof the heavy states which mediate the decay. We remind the reader that the\nheavy Higgs limit is dominated by the contribution from the longitudinal W\nbosons, which in the limit m_H >> M_W are represented by the charged Higgs\nghosts according to the equivalence theorem. The corresponding contribution is\nmissing in Gastmans, Wu and Wu as well as in the new paper by Christova and\nTodorov.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 4 Oct 2011 23:29:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 30 Oct 2014 13:52:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-10-31"}
{"id":"1110.0870","submitter":"Javier Segura","authors":"Javier Segura","title":"On bounds for solutions of monotonic first order difference-differential\n  systems","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Many special functions are solutions of first order linear systems\n$y_n'(x)=a_n(x)y_n(x)+d_n(x)y_{n-1}(x)$,\n$y_{n-1}'(x)=b_n(x)y_{n-1}(x)+e_{n}(x)y_n(x)$. We obtain bounds for the ratios\n$y_n(x)/y_{n-1}(x)$ and the logarithmic derivatives of $y_n(x)$ for solutions\nof monotonic systems satisfying certain initial conditions. For the case\n$d_n(x)e_n(x)>0$, sequences of upper and lower bounds can be obtained by\niterating the recurrence relation; for minimal solutions of the recurrence\nthese are convergent sequences. The bounds are related to the Liouville-Green\napproximation for the associated second order ODEs as well as to the asymptotic\nbehavior of the associated three-term recurrence relation as $n\\rightarrow\n+\\infty$; the bounds are sharp both as a function of $n$ and $x$. Many special\nfunctions are amenable to this analysis, and we give several examples of\napplication: modified Bessel functions, parabolic cylinder functions, Legendre\nfunctions of imaginary variable and Laguerre functions. New Tur\\'an-type\ninequalities are established from the function ratio bounds. Bounds for\nmonotonic systems with $d_n(x)e_n(x)<0$ are also given, in particular for\nHermite and Laguerre polynomials of real positive variable; in that case the\nbounds can be used for bounding the monotonic region (and then the extreme\nzeros).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 4 Oct 2011 23:38:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-10-06"}
